<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-02-26T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-02-26T15:00:00-05:00" n="542" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d542">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3268: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moore</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-02-26T15:00:00-05:00">February 26, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 3:50 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>21. This morning I saw President Leguia. The President said that he would
                            submit a report to Ambassador Figueroa on February 28. President Leguia
                            is not submitting the report as a proposition, but I personally believe
                            that he would settle the Tacna-Arica question on the basis I suggested
                            and in conformity with my 19, February 21, 4 p.m., if, in addition
                            thereto, Chile would pay $3,500,000 for the construction of a new port
                            in lieu of damages to Peruvian citizens.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
